NbS may have their place in adaptation efforts, but they need more robust evidence before we push developing nations to prioritize them. Stronger, more resilient engineered infrastructure, facilitated by economic development, will underpin the main path toward climate resiliency.
All of this equates to development, which itself increases resilience in all aspects of modern life.

Gray systems aren‚Äôt perfect, but they provide much more definite and reliable resilience. Infrastructure maximizes economic growth, wealth-building and is a main avenue through which to raise living standards and better cope with natural disasters. https://t.co/6rH2pl2aMe

Before any SIDS pours a large amount of funding and effort into NbS, it should focus on research that sufficiently measures NbS‚Äô effectiveness. And it should compare that research to data on engineered solutions that have quantifiable and proven benefits.

So far, the question of drawbacks has mostly been overlooked under the romanticized assumption that nature-based measures will do no harm. But NbS risks should be thoroughly analyzed with the same rigor that gray, engineered infrastructure risks are.

NbS also potentially come with their own set of risks, like increased mosquito, and other disease vector species that would benefit from an increase in their habitats. This is especially concerning when considering NbS near or in urban areas.

Naturalistic approaches, moreover, have unique limitations which make them more challenging for governments to implement. Many NbS benefits accrue over periods of years or decades, which makes predicting and measuring effectiveness even more difficult. https://t.co/FhLZPaz6hv

As complex networks of interacting organisms, NbS have many other context-specific natural and non-natural factors interacting with them, potentially influencing their performance and complicating accurate measurement of their efficacy.
Researchers must do more to compare NbS effectiveness with that of gray (engineered) infrastructure, which so far has been insufficiently done.

Often, coordinators can‚Äôt pre-assess NbS projects, which means that the projects have to be implemented before any measurements can even be attempted; that is a lot of time and effort to invest before the most valued benefits are seen...if they are seen.https://t.co/YsnMvJ9BWQ
Within the NbS literature, only a fairly small number of studies provide a quantitative rather than qualitative analysis of NbS co-benefits.

But when it comes to climate change, policymakers should prioritize whatever solutions are scientifically supported as the most effective, and there is still insufficient clear evidence about how much value NbS truly offer.
NbS projects are beginning to pop up across island nations to address vulnerabilities to climate change.https://t.co/jsckOr49uh

This is why the emerging focus on nature-based solutions (NbS) for SIDS is alarming. These are measures that rely on ecosystems to reduce the impact of natural disasters, preserve biodiversity and provide benefits for human well-being.

Updated building codes made a visible difference for Florida upon Hurricane Ian‚Äôs arrival.The Thames Barrier has long protected central London from flooding like the Maeslant Barrier has within the Netherlands.https://t.co/eDZzouFqTj
For decades, by contrast, richer countries have been building resilience through effective engineered infrastructure.

Infrastructure is also the foundation of economic growth and the means of recovery after disasters. SIDS already lack sufficient infrastructure for their citizens so this problem is exacerbated after natural disasters.

Why is extreme weather so much more devastating for SIDS? The key difference is infrastructure. High-income countries have much stronger, modern infrastructure that can withstand threats. More of the population in SIDS live in hazard-exposed areas without safeguards.
Average mortality from storms, floods, and droughts is 15 times lower in high-income countries than in SIDS, one of the most vulnerable groups to extreme weather. https://t.co/TnzNRwHN1q
Hurricanes are a fact of life for the Caribbean‚Äôs island nations, but their impact need not be this great.

In September and October, more than 11 million people across Puerto Rico and Cuba lost electricity when Hurricane Ian made its devastating arrival in the Caribbean. And that was just the tip of the iceberg for the damages both islands endured.https://t.co/J4fNHpohIe

It wraps up by putting the ever-present concerns of our individual CC actions to rest. If we start being more concerned with the climate, others will follow. Everything starts somewhere, and fighting CC starts with us.

It also speaks on several other things we could change in our lives to reduce our carbon footprint. These include eating more plant based foods (meats are a high emission industry), flying less often (also a high emission industry), as well as shopping more intelligently.

It then goes on to speak on renewable energy sources like solar power. I know I was concerned about the costs of such an endeavor, but the article addresses that directly, explaining that solar and renewable energy is at its cheapest point in history.

Then, it moves into the main topic: the ways we, individually, can make a difference. The first two ways include voting on legislation and politicians that will promote the battle against CC as well as accepting the fact that adjusting to being climate friendly will be tough.
The article begins by accepting the fact that CC is real and is already happening, and that we need to focus on it not tomorrow, but today.

To find out more from the NRDC's article on climate change, take a look at the link below!https://t.co/ZI4diA3AqC

This is such a valuable resource because of its easily digestible information, deep dives into otherwise basic facts and knowledge about CC, and its very fitting layout (it follows an order of logic and understanding, building its topic up as it goes along).
Concluding the article, it includes several facts about CC and then ends it with both current and possible solutions to addressing the issues of CC.

Much like other sources, it also includes a deeper look into what the effects of climate change are and will be, such as rising sea levels and endangered ecosystems. It does a wonderful job of taking fairly obvious, basic understandings of CC and taking a deeper look at them.

It then applies this same way of explanation to the causes of CC, first simply explaining how our climate actually works. Then, it takes that a step further and delves deep into both the natural and anthropogenic (man-made) causes of CC.

It explains how weather is measured in today's age, then applies that to how climate change is measured. Instead of using monitoring devices constantly, we measure long-term indications of CC, like using lake sediments and being able to understand corals and tree rings.
The article begins by doing just this! It defines CC and what some of its effects are to introduce the topic. Then it breaks down the various pieces of CC into more deep, but digestible, parts.

The National Resources Defense Council has the perfect article just for this, titled simply, "What Is Climate Change?". The article does two things at once. It talks about the basics of climate change, the more general information, but then goes in depth about those basics.

The fact that this is all coming from a government agency, no less NASA itself, is indicative of its urgency. Climate change can already be felt, NASA knows this, and it needs to be turned around before we reach those terrifying future impacts.

While the article has a strong focus on CC in the present, it doesn't shy away from giving a future heads up to what could/will happen next. Temperatures and water levels will continue to rise, weather will get more severe, wildfire season will only continue to grow longer.

The article does an incredible job of issuing a sense of urgency to its audience. If we do not include CC on the list of priorities for humanity, then CC will only worsen to a point of inevitably worse effects.

It then moves on to explain what these effects are, including: glaciers shrinking, biodiversity shifting, and stronger heat waves. The article even takes note of the fact that these symptoms and more of CC are occurring much sooner than anticipated.

"We protect us" as a mantra is not only about immediate physical security. It should also include working to protect tomorrow from belonging to the worst of humanity. It's about building a better, more just and ecologically sustainable future for ourselves and people yet to come.

Water-sourcing and purification, food production, shelter building, and security planning among many other things. It is a daunting hill to climb, significantly more than just buying a gun and training to use it. But that is the great strength of a collective approach to this.

We evolved with collective action and cooperation as being central to our survival as a species. Dog-eat-dog and myopic selfishness is not "human nature", this is just the great lie that capitalists and their bootlicking Renfields tell themselves to justify their parasitism.

Right-wing prepper spaces and thinking are inundated with this paradigm; in many ways it's foundational to their model. This is also their greatest weakness, as the romanticized lone wolf / Rambo fantasy they cling to is, in fact, a death sentence in any actual collapse scenario.

American culture pushes us to be intensely atomized and alienated from one another through many decades of hyper-individualist inculcation, such that when SHTF we immediately revert to a crabs in a pot mentality and begin fighting over scraps rather than cooperating to survive.

To be clear, this is not to deny that those people exist. They do; and as a project, the accelerationist right have a *decades*-long lead on us in this. That near-monopoly must come to an end, for if and when things begin to break down further, people must find ways to survive.

"Prepper" and "prepping" tends to evoke in the mind the popular stereotype of the wild-eyed, hyper-paranoid reactionary living in a bunker in the woods with their stockpile of canned goods, a stereotype capitalist media have done considerable work to reinforce over the years.

Much in the same way as how many on the left and within marginalized communities have begun to build an alternative to right-wing gun culture, we need to do the same thing for general preparedness and survival training.

To learn more about these tips and several more from this article, click the link below!https://t.co/phEvCFGKIp

Finally, the article concludes their list with three more tips all based on getting active in our communities to fight climate change. Vote for those who believe in and support the fight while being active in discussing CC to spread information about what we can do to fight CC.

Additionally, the article urges us to use green energy and promote those who do not use fossil fuels. We can also help to do this ourselves by growing our foods and lower meat intake (the meat production business is huge on emissions).

A few other great tips include using public transportation, sharing rides, and biking. Also, the article places an emphasis on enjoying nature instead of spending time buying and consuming. This can both make you happier and reduce your carbon footprint.

Early on in the article, a great way to reduce emissions is presented: using energy efficiently (turn off electronics when not in use, use cold water when washing clothes, etc.). This is also an ultimate price cutter, as using less electricity cheapens your bills.

A bit different than the other articles, this one doesn't contain a natural intro or conclusion, but dedicates its entire structure to 10 different effective ways that we, as individuals, can combat CC.

To conclude his article, Ortiz then addresses the concerns that what we do as individuals will have no impact on CC. When a person makes a decision to fight against CC, other people tend to follow. That can spread to many others, and soon enough we have impacted CC greatly.

A few more options Ortiz and the BBC offer include limiting flying as planes use fossil fuel to fly which causes great pollution, as well as being a smarter shopper. An example given is the clothing industry being pretty high emission based.

Ortiz then goes deeper into the individuality of the situation: what we can do in our day-to-day lives to help against CC. This can include using cost-efficient green energy (solar energy) and eating a more cautious diet (meat and dairy products come from high emission sources).

Following this introduction, Ortiz goes into the initial first few ways to fight CC, including voting for politicians who both believe in and want to fight against CC, as well as shifting funding away from organizations who have high emissions and pollution.

Ortiz begins his article by reinforcing the fact that climate change is already happening right now and our current course is unsustainable. Instead of focusing on whether we are causing climate change or not, the article claims that we should be focusing on how to deal with it.

However, that's exactly the misconception that the BBC intends to combat. In their article "Ten simple ways to act on climate change", author Diego Ortiz gives many ways that we, as individuals, can make a difference towards defeating CC, as well as how we can accomplish them.

The media should not stray from consensus science to promote narratives about ‚Äòall extremes getting more extreme‚Äô even if it makes for a more enticing headline.

So I would encourage media covering cold extremes to communicate the IPCC consensus that cold extremes are getting less extreme (warmer) and that we expect them to continue to get less extreme (warmer) in the future.
In the case of extreme cold supposedly getting colder, there are theories (#2) LOOKING for / WISHING for observations (#1) and modeling (#3) to support them, but so far, they are mostly nonexistent.
Typically in science (apart from fields like theoretical physics), you have an observation of a phenomenon and there are attempts to create elegant theories to explain that observation.
Here are the projections of changes in the coldest temperatures from physical climate models, again showing warming (#3):https://t.co/rK5YPhg5UL https://t.co/C5qP40ys8m
Here are the observations (#1) of trends in the coldest temperatures, showing warming.https://t.co/rK5YPhg5ULPanel B: https://t.co/CsGRUjNtIG

In the case of climate change causing more extreme cold, there are some theories (#2) for how this might work. The theories themselves are controversial, but more importantly, they are NOT broadly supported by observations (#1) or experimentation with physical climate models (#3)

One way to characterize the fundamentals of scientific understanding is to separate it into 3 pillars:1) Observations2) Fundamental theory3) Experimentation (done with physics-based computer models in climate science)

So why the confusion? There are some scientists/papers that advance hypotheses of how extreme cold could get colder as it warms, and this angle is just too enticing for many media outlets to resist. Thus the idea gets promoted as being much more mainstream than it actually is.

New York's regulator oversees lots of small banks, and was working closely with them in developing the guidance. It can be a proof of concept that the federal regulators pick up.This matters because many state banking regulators still deny that climate change is a threat.

The federal banking principles also only apply to large banks. Small community banks have pushed back on having any climate risk expectations applied to them, because its complicated. But regulators can't just hide their heads in the sand: climate change will hurt small banks.

Federal regulators have proposed their own guidance in the interim. But it's just high level principles. If New York's guidance is anything like what its told insurers, it will be a detailed set of expectations for how banks navigate climate change and the energy transition.

New York was already the first state to acknowledge climate risk to banks, and the first to publish detailed guidance on climate risk for insurers. Bank guidance has been in the works for over a year.

At the moment, we do not have a carbon trading system in Kenya. In June 2021, the finance minister #UkurYatani indicated there are plans to establish the Kenya Emissions Trading System to allow for carbon trading https://t.co/SPmqRKrbEH

In 2021, the former President #UhuruKenyatta  launched the National Climate Action Plan (NCAP) (2018- 2022) which charts a path towards low carbon climate resilient development in a manner that prioritizes adaptation. https://t.co/BMNjHg6II6

Carbon trading is increasingly gaining momentum in Kenya. In 2014, the World Bank and Kenya Agriculture Carbon Project (KACP) Vi Agroforestry launched a carbon trading project known as Sustainable Agricultural Land Management (SALM) for smallholder farmers from western Kenya

The CERs can then be bought by individuals and organizations to offset their own unavoidable emissions or as a contribution to the global climate action. That is #CarbonMarket  trading and its very efficient if well done in volume and traded in scale

Voluntary and incentivized collaborative approaches on carbon trading are not new. The United Nations (#UN) has in place an e-commerce carbon trading platform known as the UN Carbon Offset Program where emissions are calculated and measured in units called UN  (CERs)

These treaties establish and regulate potential multilateral carbon trading markets between member states, provide for mechanisms for monitoring #emissions and #mitigation with the purpose of reducing #greenhouse  gas emissions and promote sustainable environment development https://t.co/5RAmGvQefC

Internationally, the regulatory regime on carbon trading is anchored on Treaties such as the #KyotoProtocol to the United Nations Framework on Climate change (UNFCC) (2005), the #ParisAgreement (2016) and the Doha Amendment (2020).

Putting a price on carbon is deemed as an effective means of reducing and regulating carbon emissions and shifting industries towards use of cleaner technology. Besides promoting a clean and sustainable environment, carbon trading provides additional revenue https://t.co/mPp6Ab3A5R

Carbon trading entails offsetting the levels of carbon dioxide emission through a market system whereby carbon emission caps are set by a central authority, and carbon is given a price with the burden of paying placed on the emitter.

These two events seen side by side present tangible moments to deeply engrain deeply and widely implement climate change mitigation and adaptation strategies such as the highly beneficial carbon trading which is minimally understood and has not quite taken root in Kenya.

Concluding the article, the authors offer several solutions that are already at work or are smart decisions to make soon, including the Paris Climate Agreement and how US cities are already fighting back against CC.
Moving on from that, the article then goes into a bit of depth regarding several effects of CC, including worsening weather patterns, health risks, and endangered ecosystems.

The article follows this by going into various causes of CC, breaking it into two sections: natural causes (typical, regular changes in Earth's climate), and Anthropogenic (greenhouse gas emissions, deforestation, etc.).

The article then goes on to explain how CC is measured using paleoclimatology which includes ways such as analyzing the rings of trees or coral structures to help decipher what is really happening over time (thousands/millions of years).

In the article entitled "What Is Climate Change", authors Melissa Denchak and Jeff Turrentine help to shed some light on what CC is really all about. The article is all about CC, first explaining that all CC boils down to is changes made in/or to the climate in the long-term.

The misconception that there is increased UV radiation due to the increase of CO2 in the atmosphere, was shared among a vast majority of the participants.

Majority of people were informed of the increase of extreme weather events, the melting of the polar ice, and the expected rise of the sea level. Most believed that the rising sea level was due to the polar ice melting, but it is mainly due to the thermal expansion of sea water. https://t.co/uU5A2znHjG

Although most participants were aware that humans are the main cause of greenhouse gas emissions, the participants were less knowledgeable of the influence of natural variations as well as temperature changes of the last decades.

From the study most people were well informed on how CO2 is produced and the greenhouse effect. But few knew about other greenhouse gasses like water vapor. The misconception involving the ozone hole as the main cause of the greenhouse effect was popular among participants. https://t.co/fyA7YlxzU5

65/Pahari communities and ecologies are engaged in a powerful response to the pre-colonial, colonial and post-colonial processes, that defy renditions of regional precarity. Our labor should be to center them in our stories.

64/To chain their fluid, mobile lives, their festival of climate-society relationships, the richness of their material and more than material worlds, within the confines of village boundaries, ecological tropes and caricatures of anachronistic agrarianism.
63/But, most importantly, we need to move beyond these stories of victimization. These tales that attempt to dissolve the agency of pahari communities into biochemical indeterminacies.

62/ They need to reconcile the enduring foundational poison of caste. They need a rethinking about how sacred geographies, ethnonationalism, geopolitical insecurities and neoextractisvism is actively undermining any possibility for regional communities and ecologies to flourish.

61/The political legitimacy of imagining just futures for Pahar is tethered to aspirations of non-elite environmentalism (@DrCRampini , @PasangYangjee and I have a paper in press that highlights this)

60/Stories which support catastrophic visions of apocalypse and project solutions which support a global climate industry whose major push is to create offsets for the exploitative sins of the elite few.
59/They are funded by a global environmental politics that refuses to encounter its Malthusian, ethnonationlist, science imperialist roots.
58/  Everyday another flood of climate reductionist reports emerge. Reports like TERI‚Äôs ‚ÄòLocked Houses, Fallow Hands‚Äô is a classic example: https://t.co/s3roZSda5e
57/Sitadi, a lower caste widow from Mana said something to me that I carry with me always, ‚ÄúWhy are you so interested in the climate?‚Ä¶the climate is not what oppresses us.‚Äù

56/Additionally, communities on the ground that I have engaged with are frustrated, just as I am with this obsession of drowning their historical relational grievances in this deluge of climate change discourse.

55/Scholars like @CameliaDewan  in her masterclass dismantling of climate reductionism in Misreading the Bengal Delta have given us an ample analytical toolkit with which to avoid such climate reductionist storytelling.

54/Even as casteist violence is on the rise in UK (one of the fastest in India), the environmental imaginaries are still echoing the ‚Äòpahari-maidani‚Äô binary, failing to explore how the pahari state emerged from the anxieties of Upper Caste men.

53/Ultimately, the successes of the 70s and even the mobilization of the Uttarakhand Kranti Dal has failed to sustain itself in part due to the inherent lack of caste/class/religious reckoning in many of these movements.

52/This complication is hidden, and yet again, the agency of local paharis, who occupy a vast spectrum of identities is subjugated by lines like, ‚ÄúTheir spirits battered by recent disasters, Raini‚Äôs last inhabitants are preparing to follow in the younger generation‚Äôs footsteps‚Ä¶‚Äù
51/Migration and stories of it are being wielded by powerful elites, both pahari and maidani, to ensure the creation of the extractive frontier that they want, a Himalayan Sacrifice zone.
50/But, my point is, what we see in Uttarakhand is a spatial reconfiguration of both rurality and agrarian life, which echoes the transformations of many key structural elements.

49/...the emergence of a mercurial commercial market economy supported by motor roads, telecom infrastructure, and electrification, the political capital of creating larger blocks to engage with various organs of the state (there are others).

48/There are a lot of reasons why this is happening, which include everything from the benefits of slowly rising up the revenue district hierarchy, state resources for healthcare and education being focussed on a few key locations...

47/According to census data Uttarakhand isn‚Äôt even in the top 3 states for rural-to-urban movement. Secondly, what we really see in Uttarakhand is what we are seeing in many other parts of India, the slow demise of smaller villages and the consolidation of bigger ones.
46/The question of Ghost Villages or rural deopeopling of Uttarakhand is part of the same reductionist, sensationalist discourse.

45/The forest department (often) has the final say, in life and in death, over their denizens and any transgression from this regulatory reality leads to expensive punitive measures, of course along casteist/religious lines.

44/ What this means is, the subsistence cropping management practiced through a more commensalist ethic, since each unit loss wasn‚Äôt understood through a commercial lens, is now gone. Gone also is the ability of local families to deal with ‚Äòanimals‚Äô in any way they choose.

43/The vertical farming practiced, following transhumance, from river valley to bugyal, is mostly on its way out. The reasons are complicated: state control, ethnonationalism, high-value ag supply chains (horticulture), and the public food distribution system.

42/It is also related to the systematic culling of predators in the region through a variety of state/private interests, in an attempt to ‚Äòdomesticate‚Äô this ‚Äòunruly place‚Äô. Finally, the straying of animals onto household fields has to do with a change in pahari agrarianism.
41/But, it is also related to the public relocation programs which ‚Äòdeport‚Äô animals from cities of the plains and release them in the forests of Uttarakhand. ( See @r_gov11 's work)
40/The increase in pest animal numbers in the spring time can be causally drawn to the milding of winters, due to the movement of the westerlies towards spring.
39/For one, human and more-than-human relationships are transforming due to a host of reasons. Is climate among them. Yes, it is, but is it the key relationship? I don‚Äôt think so.

20/Reducing migration to simplistic notions of remoteness, stifles the powerful agency of local paharis. It insinuates that they are not in control of their lives, being jostled by powerful forces, moving because they have no choice. Victims of both structure and nature.

17/Migration in Uttarakhand has a variety of foundational elements. Transhumance for one, is the seasonal movement with livestock following water and pastures, which has been impacted by a variety of geopolitical events.

We should ensure the Fund is meeting industry and societal standards on climate change, while remaining a strong investor for the nation.Have a read of the full report here: https://t.co/f35sf94gzq

The Future Fund is investing Australian taxpayers' money and it is Australian taxpayers who ultimately carry the risk of its investments and bare any real-world negative impact of its decisions. That includes climate risk and the damage from a rapidly heating planet.

With this in mind CPD recommends an independent review of the Fund's climate risk response - similar to reviews carried out recently in NSW and Norway - ahead of the mandate being reissued with stronger climate change direction.

More importantly, there is significant scope to issue stronger climate risk direction in the Fund's investment mandate, including establishing portfolio targets that reflect Australia's emissions reduction commitments.

The Finance Minister can immediately request the Fund issue climate risk disclosure. With this reporting to be mandated in the Australian market, this direction would help the Fund prepare, ensure greater transparency and avoid double standards between public and private.

The report then detailed how the Australian Government could issue clearer guidance to the Future Fund to help the Board strengthen its climate change response without impinging on the necessary independence of day-to-day investment decisions.

When we assessed the Future Fund's climate activities against the Expectations Ladder of The Investor Agenda's Investor Climate Action Plans program we found it reflected a partial response to early stage practice. https://t.co/iAfa3pFwAX

But across disclosure, collaboration and strategy (including the adoption of emissions reduction goals in its portfolio) it is trailing other publicly-owned investors and the industry more generally in aspects of its response.

With what is available to review it is clear the Fund is taking some concrete and positive steps on climate risk such as scenario testing, risk weighting in investment decisions and some company engagement.

However, this was at times difficult because the Fund does not issue climate risk disclosure (and holds a position that it does not need to) or have a published dedicated climate strategy - both concerns in themselves and out of step with industry practice.

Integrating and addressing portfolio climaterisks and opportunities is now well establishedinvestment practice and the Fund‚Äôs response onthese issues can therefore be considered against other institutional investors and a growing set ofindustry standards and guidance.

First the report looks at the Fund's climate response to date. This was done with reference to the Board's legislative requirement to seek to ‚Äúmaximise the return earned on the Fund over the long term, consistent with international best practice for institutional investment.‚Äù
